<div style=" text-align:center;">
<h1>HOLI</h1>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center">
<img src="https://www.daysoftheyear.com/cdn-cgi/image/dpr=1%2Cf=auto%2Cfit=cover%2Ch=675%2Cq=85%2Cw=1200/wp-content/uploads/holi-india-e1706805463210.jpg" alt="">
</div>

<div>
<p>
Holi is one of the most joyful and colorful festivals of India. It is also known as the Festival of Colors and is celebrated in the month of March, marking the arrival of spring. People of all ages participate in this festival with great enthusiasm.

The festival has both religious and cultural significance. According to Hindu mythology, Holi is celebrated to remember the victory of good over evil. The story of Prahlad and Holika is closely linked to Holi. Prahlad’s devotion to Lord Vishnu saved him, while Holika, who symbolized evil, was destroyed in fire. The night before Holi, people light bonfires called Holika Dahan to represent this victory of truth and goodness.

On the day of Holi, people play with colors, water balloons, and sprays. Friends and families come together, apply gulal (colored powder) on each other, and enjoy festive sweets like gujiya. The festival brings laughter, fun, and unity, as differences of caste, class, and age disappear in the spirit of celebration.

Holi also has a deeper meaning—it teaches us to forget past quarrels, forgive others, and start fresh relationships. It spreads happiness, peace, and brotherhood in society.

In conclusion, Holi is not just about colors and fun, but also about love, togetherness, and the triumph of good over evil. It is a festival that truly reflects the vibrant culture and unity of India.
 </p>
